column1: Bio: An elf that has opted for the adventurer life, despite his weak physique. He takes on the easy role of detecting the locations of monsters nearby.

Flower on head: The flower on his head allows him to detect monsters - it can be detached too! Though, why can't anyone just pop such a flower on their head and get the same ability? Well, the magical flower chooses you, not the other way around. And this flower happened to pick Zephyr, a weak lazy guy. Quite a few adventurers were pissed they couldn't get chosen...!
Personality: Lazy, carefree, and always goes with the flow. They don't like to put more effort than they have to.

Clothes: They hate tight and restrictive clothes, so he wears loose, open outfits. Though, this backfires in colder areas he has to travel to... and then an adventure teammate has to lend them a jacket or sweater.

Xumon: They met Xumon a few times when they were assigned on the same adventurer missions. ""They seem to like taking the easy route, like me hehe. But playing instruments? Ahh... nevermind, that's still a lot of work.""

Retrieves a group of adjacent monster cards to the specified zone position.
- pos (number): The zone position to check for adjacent cards (0 to 4).
- adjCards (Group): A group of adjacent monster cards, or nil if no adjacent cards are found.
- This function checks the adjacent zones (pos+1 and pos-1) for monster cards that are face-up.
- Only valid zone positions from 0 to 4 are considered. If the specified position is outside this range, nil is returned.
local adjCards = Group.CreateGroup() -- Group to store the adjacent cards
local seq = Duel.GetFieldCardSequence(pos) -- Get the sequence of the specified position
if seq and seq >= 0 and seq <= 4 then
local adjPos1 = pos + 1 -- Position of the adjacent zone (pos+1)
local adjPos2 = pos - 1 -- Position of the adjacent zone (pos-1)
local adjCard1 = Duel.GetFieldCard(tp, adjPos1, LOCATION_MZONE) -- Get the card in the adjacent zone (pos+1)
local adjCard2 = Duel.GetFieldCard(tp, adjPos2, LOCATION_MZONE) -- Get the card in the adjacent zone (pos-1)
adjCards:AddCard(adjCard1) -- Add the adjacent card (pos+1) to the group
adjCards:AddCard(adjCard2) -- Add the adjacent card (pos-1) to the group
return adjCards -- Return the group of adjacent cards
return nil -- No adjacent cards found, return nil
Retorna um grupo de cartas de monstro adjacentes à posição de zona especificada.
- pos (número): A posição da zona a verificar para cartas adjacentes (0 a 4).
- adjCards (Grupo): Um grupo de cartas de monstro adjacentes, ou nil se nenhuma carta adjacente for encontrada.
- Esta função verifica as zonas adjacentes (pos+1 e pos-1) em busca de cartas de monstro viradas para cima.
- Somente posições válidas de zona de 0 a 4 são consideradas. Se a posição especificada estiver fora dessa faixa, nil é retornado.
local adjCards = Group.CreateGroup() -- Grupo para armazenar as cartas adjacentes
local seq = Duel.GetFieldCardSequence(pos) -- Obtém a sequência da posição especificada
if seq and seq >= 0 and seq <= 4 then
local adjPos1 = pos + 1 -- Posição da zona adjacente (pos+1)
local adjPos2 = pos - 1 -- Posição da zona adjacente (pos-1)
local adjCard1 = Duel.GetFieldCard(tp, adjPos1, LOCATION_MZONE) -- Obtém a carta na zona adjacente (pos+1)
local adjCard2 = Duel.GetFieldCard(tp, adjPos2, LOCATION_MZONE) -- Obtém a carta na zona adjacente (pos-1)
adjCards:AddCard(adjCard1) -- Adiciona a carta adjacente (pos+1) ao grupo
adjCards:AddCard(adjCard2) -- Adiciona a carta adjacente (pos-1) ao grupo
return adjCards -- Retorna o grupo de cartas adjacentes
return nil -- Nenhuma carta adjacente encontrada, retorna nil

# Keys common to some of the core services that we always to automatically restart on failure

<<: *common-keys-core # See EXTENSION FIELDS at the top
# Allow these IPs to set the X-Forwarded-* headers - Cloudflare IPs: https://www.cloudflare.com/ips/
- --log.level=DEBUG # (Default: error) DEBUG, INFO, WARN, ERROR, FATAL, PANIC
- --providers.docker.endpoint=unix:///var/run/docker.sock # Use Docker Socket Proxy instead for improved security
# - --providers.docker.endpoint=tcp://socket-proxy:2375 # Use this instead of the previous line if you have socket proxy.
# Add dns-cloudflare as default certresolver for all services. Also enables TLS and no need to specify on individual services
# - --entrypoints.https.http.tls.domains[1].main=$DOMAINNAME2 # Pulls main cert for second domain
# - --entrypoints.https.http.tls.domains[1].sans=*.$DOMAINNAME2 # Pulls wildcard cert for second domain
- --providers.file.directory=/rules # Load dynamic configuration from one or more .toml or .yml files in a directory
# - --providers.file.filename=/path/to/file # Load dynamic configuration from a file
- --providers.file.watch=true # Only works on top level files in the rules folder
#- --certificatesResolvers.dns-cloudflare.acme.caServer=https://acme-staging-v02.api.letsencrypt.org/directory # LetsEncrypt Staging Server - uncomment when testing
- --certificatesResolvers.dns-cloudflare.acme.dnsChallenge.delayBeforeCheck=90 # To delay DNS check and reduce LE hitrate

- /var/run/docker.sock:/var/run/docker.sock:ro # If you use Docker Socket Proxy, comment this line out

The dystopian version of superintelligence is illustrated with frequency by leaders in the technology industry, and is famously depicted by Hollywood in films like Terminator,
or more recently Ex Machina, and even the Avengers. The “furious deity A.I.” is a story you know, because it is the story you are constantly told: we build the thinking machine,
it surpasses our abilities in every way, and it destroys us for one of any number of reasons.Maybe it perceives us as a threat. Maybe we’re just in its way,
and it hardly perceives us at all — mankind, a disposable insect race.
There are of course many arguments in opposition to the now ubiquitous concept of our apocalypse by artificial intelligence.

The dystopian version of superintelligence is illustrated with frequency by leaders in the technology industry, and is famously depicted by Hollywood in films like Terminator, or more recently Ex Machina, and even the Avengers. The “angry god A.I.” is a story you know, because it is the story you are constantly told: we build the thinking machine, it surpasses our abilities in every way, and it destroys us for one of any number of reasons.
Maybe it perceives us as a threat. Maybe we’re just in its way, and it hardly perceives us at all — humanity, a disposable insect race.

There are of course many arguments in opposition to the now ubiquitous concept of our apocalypse by artificial intelligence. I myself have called into question the logic of such dystopian arguments in Anatomy of Next. But our subject here is less pertaining to the nature of the conscious machine than it is to the way we talk about this subject, and what it means. First, consider that most of the artificial intelligence depicted in culture looks human, a representation with no basis in technological reality. Then, the true scope of the Singularity is almost impossible to predict, which begs a question: where are these opinions about the broadly unknowable coming from?
